⚡ Spring Boot Starter Cheat Sheet
🔹 Core Starters
spring‑boot‑starter — core starter (logging + auto‑config)

spring‑boot‑starter-web — REST APIs (MVC + Tomcat + JSON)

spring‑boot‑starter-test — JUnit, Mockito, Spring Test

spring‑boot‑starter-validation — Bean validation (@Valid, @NotNull)

🔹 Database Starters
spring‑boot‑starter-data-jpa — JPA + Hibernate

spring‑boot‑starter-jdbc — JDBC Template

spring‑boot‑starter-data-mongodb — MongoDB

spring‑boot‑starter-data-redis — Redis

🔹 Web & UI Starters
spring‑boot‑starter-webflux — Reactive APIs

spring‑boot‑starter-thymeleaf — HTML template engine

spring‑boot‑starter-mustache — alternative template engine

🔹 Security & Authentication
spring‑boot‑starter-security — authentication & authorization

spring‑boot‑starter-oauth2-client — Google/GitHub login

spring‑boot‑starter-oauth2-resource-server — JWT validation

🔹 Messaging
spring‑boot‑starter-amqp — RabbitMQ

spring‑boot‑starter-kafka — Kafka

🔹 Email & Communication
spring‑boot‑starter-mail — send emails

🔹 Monitoring & Dev Tools
spring‑boot‑starter-actuator — health checks & metrics

spring‑boot‑starter-devtools — auto‑restart during development

⭐ The 5 Starters You Must Memorize
If you remember only these, you’re good:

spring‑boot‑starter-web

spring‑boot‑starter-data-jpa

spring‑boot‑starter-test

spring‑boot‑starter-validation

spring‑boot‑starter-security

These five cover 80% of backend development.

⭐ How to Use a Starter (Example)
Add this to your pom.xml:

xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-web</artifactId>
</dependency>
Spring Boot automatically brings:

Spring MVC

Tomcat

Jackson

Logging

Validation

All compatible versions — no manual setup.

⭐ Final Takeaway
Spring Boot starters make your life easier by:

Bundling dependencies

Managing versions

